liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Myles Houlbrook-Walk Anthony Albanese has visited one of the biggest mosques in Australia speaking to muslims at Friday prayers about The Voice to Parliament. In his pitch he spoke of the long standing relationship between Muslims and First Australians before European colonisation. Forged between Yolŋu from North East Arnhem Land and traders from Makassar. The Lakemba Mosque was packed for regular Friday prayers where Mr Albanes urged voters in south-west Sydney asking the hundreds in attendance to "appeal to our better angles." "This referendum won't be decided by politicians it will be decided by everyone in this room above 18," he said. Mr Albanese also claimed that regardless of progressive or conservative arguments for the No vote it would leave the country stuck in addressing disadvantage. "There is no progressive Yes or progressive No." "Voting No leaves us nowhere. No recognition. No way forward." Alongside the PM President of the Australian National Imams Council Sheikh Shady Alsuleiman called on fellow muslims to vote yes. "We are committed to the Voice and we will say Yes to the Voice." "Inshallah on October 15 we will wake up and every single Australian will see the success of the Voice." The Labor Party is working hard to grow the Yes vote among multicultural and diverse communities. Yesterday Indigenous Affairs Minister Linda Burney addressed a group of about a hundred older Chinese-Australians with her speech translated into Mandarin and Cantonese.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Albanese says 'voting No will leave us nowhere'

children.content: Prime Minister at Lakemba Mosque today.
(ABC News: Myles Houlbrook-Walk)
Reporting by Myles Houlbrook-Walk
Anthony Albanese has visited one of the biggest mosques in Australia speaking to muslims at Friday prayers about The Voice to Parliament.
In his pitch he spoke of the long standing relationship between Muslims and First Australians before European colonisation.
Forged between Yolŋu from North East Arnhem Land and traders from Makassar.
The Lakemba Mosque was packed for regular Friday prayers where Mr Albanes urged voters in south-west Sydney asking the hundreds in attendance to "appeal to our better angles."
"This referendum won't be decided by politicians it will be decided by everyone in this room above 18," he said.
(ABC News: Myles Houlbrook-Walk)
Mr Albanese also claimed that regardless of progressive or conservative arguments for the No vote it would leave the country stuck in addressing disadvantage.
"There is no progressive Yes or progressive No."
"Voting No leaves us nowhere. No recognition. No way forward."
Alongside the PM President of the Australian National Imams Council Sheikh Shady Alsuleiman called on fellow muslims to vote yes.
"We are committed to the Voice and we will say Yes to the Voice."
"Inshallah on October 15 we will wake up and every single Australian will see the success of the Voice."
(ABC News: Myles Houlbrook-Walk)
The Labor Party is working hard to grow the Yes vote among multicultural and diverse communities.
Yesterday Indigenous Affairs Minister Linda Burney addressed a group of about a hundred older Chinese-Australians with her speech translated into Mandarin and Cantonese.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The government says the Voice is designed to improve Indigenous lives and Close the Gap. Carly Williams says while some Close the Gap targets are on track others are going backwards. "What we are seeing worsening is early childhood development, adults in prison, children in out-of-home care and Indigenous suicide rates," she said. "We don'thave a crystal ball to know if the Voice is going to magically fix this, especially how fast that can happen." Fran Kelly says the argument put forward by those supporting the Voice is that is will be hearing from grassroots communities that will be coming up with ideas on what would work. Williams says that history shows that when mob are part of the decision-making process it results in the most fruitful outcomes. "This is aboutself-determination, that is what the government and Yes advocates say," she says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: How can a Voice improve Indigenous lives?
